{"tree":{"type":"node","kind":"SOURCE_FILE","width":9,"children":[{"type":"token","kind":"WHITESPACE","text":"\n","width":1},{"type":"node","kind":"LET_BINDING","width":8,"children":[{"type":"token","kind":"IDENT_EXPR","text":"let","width":3},{"type":"token","kind":"WHITESPACE","text":" ","width":1},{"type":"node","kind":"ERROR","width":0,"children":[]},{"type":"token","kind":"IDENT_EXPR","text":"=","width":1},{"type":"token","kind":"WHITESPACE","text":" ","width":1},{"type":"node","kind":"INT_LITERAL","width":2,"children":[{"type":"token","kind":"INT_LITERAL","text":"42","width":2}]}]}]},"diagnostics":[{"kind":{"id":"E0007","name":"invalid-pattern","expected":"identifier or pattern","found":{"kind":"=","text":"="},"fix":"add a variable name, \"_\" (underscore) to ignore it.","hint":"\nThe left side of a let-expression allows you to pattern match on values to assign them to variables, but also to deconstruct them and access their inner values.\n\n   ```ocaml\n   let variable = 42 in\n   let { x; _ } = point in\n   let Some x = optional in\n   (* ... *)\n   ```\n\nBeware that pattern matching on only one of many possible values will lead to runtime errors!\n"},"span":{"start":3,"end":3}}]}
